    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Zoological Society’s Gardens, | Regent’s Park, | London, N.W.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. <hi rend="print">18</hi>67.</date>
                    <salute>My Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>In reply to your note<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I beg to say the name of the birds in question is the <hi rend="underline">Knot</hi> (Calidris canutus)   I have kept eight or nine of them and out of this number only one put on any of the breeding or summer dress,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> while in the same cage <hi rend="underline">two</hi> <hi rend="underline">Turnstones</hi> (Strepsilas interpres)<ref target="#foot.f3"/> <hi rend="underline">both assumed their breeding plumage in the Summer</hi>, all the birds appear equally well in health and condition, the <hi rend="underline">Turnstones</hi> have now moulted into the winter garb, the coloured worsted rags &amp;c shall be tried immediately.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>believe me to be | Yours faithfully | A. D. Bartlett. <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Cha<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>. Darwin Esq</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note><hi rend="italic">Top of letter</hi>: ‘If the summer Plumage of the Knot, is the same in 2 sexes, we learn that the summer plumage is nuptial &amp; common to the 2 sexes—as occurs with a multitude of Birds.—’<ref target="#foot.f5"/> <hi rend="italic">ink</hi></note>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="./DCP-LETT-5719.xml" resp="#automat">Letter to A. D. Bartlett, 9 December [1867]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD referred to the bird by its older name, <hi rend="italic">Tringa canutus</hi>, in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 2: 82, citing Bartlett on specimens in the Zoological Gardens in London failing to develop their summer plumage.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Strepsilas interpres</hi> is now <hi rend="italic">Arenaria interpres</hi> (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_651.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Birds of the world</hi></ref> 3: 515–16).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5719.xml" resp="#automat">letter to A. D. Bartlett, 9 December [1867]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">These points are developed more fully in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 2: 81–2.</note>
        </div>        
            
